Muhammad Usama Anjum <usama.anjum@arm.com>

[PATCH v2 0/3] mm: Free contiguous order-0 pages efficiently

The approach is sound and the benchmark numbers are compelling.  A few
things to clarify:

---

[PATCH v2 1/3] mm/page_alloc: Optimize free_contig_range()

> diff --git a/include/linux/gfp.h b/include/linux/gfp.h
> @@ -467,6 +467,8 @@ void free_contig_frozen_range(unsigned long pfn,
>  void free_contig_range(unsigned long pfn, unsigned long nr_pages);
>  #endif
>
> +unsigned long __free_contig_range(unsigned long pfn, unsigned long nr_pages);

The declaration of __free_contig_range() is placed after the
#endif /* CONFIG_CONTIG_ALLOC */, so it is visible unconditionally.
Patch 2 calls it unconditionally from vfree() too.  If the
implementation in page_alloc.c sits inside the #ifdef CONFIG_CONTIG_ALLOC
block (which currently spans lines 6787-7337), then any config built
without MEMORY_ISOLATION+COMPACTION and without CMA will fail to link
when vmalloc.c references the symbol.

Is free_prepared_contig_range() and __free_contig_range() placed
*before* that block so that they are always compiled in, regardless of
CONFIG_CONTIG_ALLOC?

---

[PATCH v2 2/3] vmalloc: Optimize vfree

> -	for (i = 0; i < vm->nr_pages; i++) {
> -		struct page *page = vm->pages[i];
>
>  		BUG_ON(!page);
> -		if (!(vm->flags & VM_MAP_PUT_PAGES))
> -			mod_lruvec_page_state(page, NR_VMALLOC, -1);
> -		__free_page(page);
> -		cond_resched();
> -	}

The old loop called cond_resched() after every single page free.  The
new loop accumulates pfns across vm->pages[] and only calls
__free_contig_range() at segment boundaries.  For a large vmalloc
region backed by heavily fragmented physical memory on a PREEMPT_NONE
kernel, both the accumulation loop (doing mod_lruvec_page_state() per
page) and the per-segment __free_contig_range() calls (doing
free_pages_prepare() per page plus lock acquisitions per chunk) run
without any scheduling point.

Was dropping cond_resched() a deliberate choice?  If so, a short
comment explaining why it is safe to remove it (e.g. the new path is
fast enough that the latency is bounded) would help reviewers and
bisectors in the future.

> +		for (i = 1; i < vm->nr_pages; i++) {
> +			page = vm->pages[i];
> +			BUG_ON(!page);
> +			if (account)
> +				mod_lruvec_page_state(page, NR_VMALLOC, -1);
> +			pfn = page_to_pfn(page);
> +			if (start_pfn + nr == pfn) {
> +				nr++;
> +				continue;
> +			}
> +			__free_contig_range(start_pfn, nr);
> +			start_pfn = pfn;
> +			nr = 1;

nr is declared as int while __free_contig_range() takes unsigned long
nr_pages.  In practice vm->nr_pages is unsigned int and bounded well
below INT_MAX, so the conversion is harmless, but declaring nr as
unsigned int (or unsigned long) would avoid any implicit sign-extension
ambiguity.

---

[PATCH v2 3/3] mm/page_alloc: Optimize __free_contig_frozen_range()

> +	for (i = 0; i < nr_pages; i++, page++) {
> +		if (free_pages_prepare(page, 0)) {
> +			if (!start)
> +				start = page;
> +		} else if (start) {
> +			free_prepared_contig_range(start, page - start);
> +			start = NULL;
> +		}
> +	}
> +
> +	if (start)
> +		free_prepared_contig_range(start, page - start);

The expression `page - start` has type ptrdiff_t (signed) and is
passed where free_prepared_contig_range() expects unsigned long.
Since start is always assigned before page can advance beyond it,
the value is always positive and the implicit conversion is correct.
An explicit cast to unsigned long would silence any compiler warnings
and make the intent explicit.

Verified: free_pages_prepare() calls __free_pages_prepare(page, 0,
FPI_NONE), matching the flags used by the old free_frozen_pages() path.
The HWPoison handling is correct: poisoned pages cause a false return,
the pending prepared run is flushed before the bad page, and a fresh
run starts after it.  The post-loop flush of the final run is present
and correct.

Author: Kanchana P. Sridhar <kanchanapsridhar2026@gmail.com>

[PATCH 1/2] mm: zswap: Tie per-CPU acomp_ctx lifetime to the pool.

The core approach -- keeping acomp_ctx alive until pool destruction so
zswap_compress/decompress never race with teardown -- is correct.
Removing the acomp_ctx_get_cpu_lock() retry loop is justified because
there is no longer a zswap_cpu_comp_dead() that can race to zero
acomp_ctx->req under a compress/decompress caller.

One concern about acomp_ctx_dealloc():

> +static void acomp_ctx_dealloc(struct crypto_acomp_ctx *acomp_ctx)
> +{
> +	if (IS_ERR_OR_NULL(acomp_ctx))
> +		return;
> +
> +	if (!IS_ERR_OR_NULL(acomp_ctx->req))
> +		acomp_request_free(acomp_ctx->req);
> +
> +	if (!IS_ERR_OR_NULL(acomp_ctx->acomp))
> +		crypto_free_acomp(acomp_ctx->acomp);
> +
> +	kfree(acomp_ctx->buffer);
> +}

Unlike the old zswap_cpu_comp_dead(), which copied the pointers to
locals, zeroed the acomp_ctx fields under the mutex, and then freed
via the locals, acomp_ctx_dealloc() frees through the live fields
without zeroing them afterward.

If the new zswap_cpu_comp_prepare() writes directly into acomp_ctx->acomp
and acomp_ctx->buffer (as the patch 2 context confirms it does), and then
the req allocation fails, the fail path calls acomp_ctx_dealloc().  That
frees acomp_ctx->acomp but leaves it as a stale non-NULL, non-ERR_PTR
value -- a dangling pointer.  If a subsequent call to acomp_ctx_dealloc()
is made for the same slot (e.g. from a pool error-cleanup path iterating
for_each_possible_cpu), the IS_ERR_OR_NULL() guard passes for a dangling
pointer and crypto_free_acomp() is called on already-freed memory.
crypto_free_acomp() only skips the free for NULL and ERR_PTR; it does
not handle stale valid pointers.

Could you confirm that the error-cleanup path in zswap_pool_create()
does not call acomp_ctx_dealloc() for CPUs whose
zswap_cpu_comp_prepare() already invoked it from the fail path?

The safest fix is to null out the fields after freeing inside
acomp_ctx_dealloc(), mirroring the pattern zswap_cpu_comp_dead() used:

    if (!IS_ERR_OR_NULL(acomp_ctx->req)) {
        acomp_request_free(acomp_ctx->req);
        acomp_ctx->req = NULL;
    }
    if (!IS_ERR_OR_NULL(acomp_ctx->acomp)) {
        crypto_free_acomp(acomp_ctx->acomp);
        acomp_ctx->acomp = NULL;
    }
    kfree(acomp_ctx->buffer);
    acomp_ctx->buffer = NULL;

[ ... ]

[PATCH 2/2] mm: zswap: Consistently use IS_ERR_OR_NULL() to check
            acomp_ctx resources.

> -	if (IS_ERR(acomp_ctx->acomp)) {
> +	if (IS_ERR_OR_NULL(acomp_ctx->acomp)) {
>  		pr_err("could not alloc crypto acomp %s : %pe\n",
>  				pool->tfm_name, acomp_ctx->acomp);
>  		ret = PTR_ERR(acomp_ctx->acomp);
>  		goto fail;

crypto_alloc_acomp_node() is documented to return ERR_PTR on failure,
never NULL (include/crypto/acompress.h: "IS_ERR() is true in case of
an error, PTR_ERR() returns the error code").  So the added NULL branch
of IS_ERR_OR_NULL() can never trigger in practice.

However, if it did trigger, PTR_ERR(NULL) == 0, so ret would be 0 and
zswap_cpu_comp_prepare() would return success to the cpuhp framework
with acomp_ctx->acomp == NULL.  The pool slot would be broken and
subsequent compress/decompress would fault on the NULL pointer.

Since the NULL case is currently unreachable, this is latent rather
than active.  But it seems cleaner to keep IS_ERR() for acomp (where
the API guarantees ERR_PTR, never NULL) and use IS_ERR_OR_NULL() only
for req (which is documented to return NULL on failure).

> -	if (!acomp_ctx->req) {
> +	if (IS_ERR_OR_NULL(acomp_ctx->req)) {

This change is safe: acomp_request_alloc() returns NULL on failure and
never an ERR_PTR (include/crypto/acompress.h: "NULL in case of an
error"), so IS_ERR_OR_NULL() is equivalent to !req here.
